          "body": "Commandments 6-9 are short, sharp, and outward — murder, adultery, theft, false witness — each two words in Hebrew. The tenth (v. 17) breaks the pattern. It is the longest of the social commands, it lists specific objects (house, wife, servants, ox, donkey, anything), and it forbids not an act but a desire. \"You shall not covet\" is the commandment that makes the whole law inescapable. Paul's testimony in Romans 7:7-11 fastens on this very command — it was \"You shall not covet\" that exposed indwelling sin and killed his self-righteousness. The tenth commandment functions like a back door into the first: ultimately, all coveting is idolatry (Colossians 3:5), the displacement of God by what we want. The Decalogue's outer ring of forbidden acts ends in the inner chamber of forbidden desires, and there every reader meets himself."
