          "title": "The altar regulations preach the gospel of approach",
          "body": "Most readers ignore verses 22-26, treating them as anticlimactic ceremonial detail. They are not. Having forbidden idolatrous worship (no silver and gold gods, v. 23), God prescribes the form of legitimate approach: an altar of earth or undressed stone, low to the ground, requiring no human craft to dignify it. The prohibition on cut stones (v. 25) and on stepped altars (v. 26) is a polemic against the elaborate worship installations of the surrounding nations — Canaanite high places, Egyptian temple platforms, Mesopotamian ziggurats. Israelite worship will not be a stage for human glory. The God who has redeemed by His own arm will be approached on terms that give no occasion for human boasting. The altar is austerely plain because the gospel it foreshadows is the work of God alone — a principle finally fulfilled at a cross where the only human contribution was the sin that put Him there."
